media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[2]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[Photo by Sam Rutherford]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[Side view of the Galaxy Watch 6 and Watch 6 Classic on plastic stands, showing their lugs and buttons.]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[Samsung Galaxy Watch 6 and Galaxy Watch 6 Classic]]></media:title></media:content></item><item><title><![CDATA[The best WiFi extenders in 2023]]></title><description type="html"><![CDATA[<p>可靠的家庭互联网连接从未如此重要。现在，我们中的许多人都在家兼职或全职工作，而其他人则越来越多地使用智能设备来支持他们的家。此外，我们一般都拥有更多的联网设备——手机、平板电脑、游戏机、电视等等，所有这些都同时连接到我们家的无线网络。在设置和维护所有技术时，您可能会发现家中某些角落存在死角或 WiFi 信号较弱，或者临时家庭办公室的信号覆盖不稳定。根据您住所的大小，郊区的 WiFi 信号强度可能很差。</p><p>这就是 WiFi 范围扩展器的用武之地。顾名思义，这些相对实惠的小工具可以扩展您的家庭网络以提供更广泛的覆盖范围。这些 WiFi 增强器可以为您提供以前从未使用过的地方的连接，例如车库、后院和房屋最远的角落。与当今许多最新的网状网络系统相比，它们的价格低廉。让我们详细分析一下这些小工具的工作原理、在选择它们之前应考虑的事项以及我们测试过的最佳 WiFi 扩展器。</p><span id="end-legacy-contents"></span><h2> WiFi 扩展器如何工作？</h2><p>这些方便的无线设备正如其名称所暗示的那样：扩展您的 WiFi 网络，使其覆盖您家中的更多区域。大多数 WiFi 扩展器插入交流电源插座并连接到您现有的网络，这样它们就可以将其重新广播到仅靠路由器可能无法很好覆盖的地点。根据经验，通过将扩展器放置在路由器和您要修复的死区之间的中间位置，您将获得最佳结果。</p><p>关于 WiFi 扩展器（有时也称为“中继器”）需要注意的一件重要事情是，它们中的大多数在重新广播现有网络时实际上会创建一个新的 WiFi 网络。该网络将有一个新名称（通常是您的默认网络名称，末尾附加有 EXT，除非您更改它），这意味着您在家中的不同部分时必须连接到不同的网络。虽然这是为了提高覆盖范围而做出的一个小小的权衡，但有些人会比其他人更不方便。</p><p>如果您希望在家中拥有一个更大的网络，那么最好升级到网状 WiFi。 Mesh 系统配有一个主路由器和接入点，默认情况下，它们会创建一个大型 WiFi 系统，整个家庭都可以访问该系统。但这也意味着设备更加昂贵，而且可能更加复杂。到目前为止，网状系统比简单的 WiFi 扩展器更昂贵，而且您可能必须与 ISP 合作才能让您家的现有网络在新路由器上运行。</p><h2> WiFi 扩展器需要注意什么</h2><h3>速度</h3><p>如今的扩展器可以支持单频、双频或三频 WiFi，并且它们会告诉您它们在所有可用频段上支持的最大速度。例如，一台双频设备可能在 2.4GHz 频段上支持 600Mbps 的速度，在 5GHz 频段上支持高达 1300Mbps 的速度，合计最大速度为 1900Mbps。为了获得最佳性能，您需要使用速度尽可能最高的 WiFi 扩展器（正如您所料，这些扩展器往往成本更高）。</p><p>然而，重要的是要记住，WiFi 扩展器并不是真正的“信号增强器”，因为它们的设计目的不是为了<em>提高</em>整个家庭的速度。事实上，您可能会发现扩展器的网络速度比路由器的速度慢。相反，扩展器旨在增加整个家庭的 WiFi 覆盖范围，使其成为填补盲区的理想选择。</p><h3>支持设备的范围和数量</h3><p>由于游戏的名称是覆盖区域，因此记下设备的范围非常重要。根据您的房屋和财产的大小，您可能只需要最多 1,200 平方英尺的覆盖范围。但那些拥有较大房屋的人会希望购买一个可以支持超过 2,000 平方英尺的覆盖范围的扩展器。</p><p>同样，那些拥有大量小工具的人会需要一个可以同时处理所有小工具的扩展器。如果您大部分时间都在手机或笔记本电脑上度过，并且可能每天通过智能电视观看几个小时的 Netflix 节目，那么您可以使用功能更有限的扩展器。智能家居爱好者和科技爱好者应该投资一款不会在几十个连接设备的压力下屈服的产品。如果您计划将家中某个部分的所有设备连接到扩展器的网络，而不是直接连接到 WiFi 路由器，这一点尤其重要。</p><h3>设计</h3><p>WiFi 扩展器领域的设计并没有太多创新。今天您会发现的大多数都是圆角矩形，大约与您的手大小相同，可插入标准交流电源插座。它们通常有一些指示灯，可以显示扩展器何时连接、信号强度有多强以及何时出现问题，有些甚至还有可移动天线，公司声称这些天线可以提供更好的 WiFi 覆盖范围。</p><p>除此之外，茶几或桌子上还有极少数独立的 WiFi 扩展器，它们看起来与普通的路由器非常相似。但请不要误会，任何标记为扩展器或“中继器”的东西都需要锚路由器才能工作。</p><p>大多数 WiFi 扩展器的另一个便利功能是额外的以太网端口（或几个）。如果您将扩展器连接到路由器，您就可以将其用作 WiFi 接入点，或者将其用作适配器，为电视、智能家居集线器或游戏机等设备提供与互联网的硬连线连接。毫不奇怪，这种有线连接通常可为您提供尽可能最快的速度，因此您可能希望将其用于最重要的设备。</p><h2> Engadget精选</h2><h2>最适合大多数人：TP-Link AX3000 WiFi 6 扩展器（RE700X 或 RE705X）</h2><p><core-commerce id="16765d91533f4fcf8768ad23d14d5f3b" data-type="product-list"></p><p> TP-Link 旗下有一系列 WiFi 扩展器，但最适合大多数人的可能是这款 AX3000 型号，它有两种版本： <a data-i13n="cpos:1;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:;" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9UUC1MaW5rLUV4dGVuZGVyLVJFNzAwWC1CZWFtZm9ybWluZy1Db21wYXRpYmxlL2RwL0IwOVY0NTVLWjI_dGg9MSZ0YWc9Z2RndDBjLXAtby1xYS0yMCIsImNvbnRlbnRVdWlkIjoiZjUzN2MwYzItYmNlNS00MjgxLThkMjctNzA2NGY1Y2ZhOGEyIn0&amp;signature=AQAAAUe5nd9UkEQ1ewtCAH9V6r48yPWhyEVKP_2EplaEQ7Ye&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FTP-Link-Extender-RE700X-Beamforming-Compatible%2Fdp%2FB09V455KZ2%3Fth%3D1">RE700X</a>和<a data-i13n="cpos:2;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Best Buy;elmt:;" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=5e0bed65-d2f8-4b34-9b8f-955218c0e37a&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Best+Buy&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI1ZTBiZWQ2NS1kMmY4LTRiMzQtOWI4Zi05NTUyMThjMGUzN2EiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmVzdGJ1eS5jb20vc2l0ZS90cC1saW5rLWF4MzAwMC1kdWFsLWJhbmQtd2ktZmktNi1yYW5nZS1leHRlbmRlci13aGl0ZS82NTAyMDYwLnA_c2t1SWQ9NjUwMjA2MCIsImNvbnRlbnRVdWlkIjoiZjUzN2MwYzItYmNlNS00MjgxLThkMjctNzA2NGY1Y2ZhOGEyIn0&amp;signature=AQAAAYVGsI8lfbnl01eY436Xu3EWiFUED6Lj7vz9xBtkcuZ5&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bestbuy.com%2Fsite%2Ftp-link-ax3000-dual-band-wi-fi-6-range-extender-white%2F6502060.p%3FskuId%3D6502060">RE705X</a> 。两款扩展器具有相同的规格，包括 WiFi 6 支持，但 705X 的设计略有不同，两侧都有拉出式天线。我测试了 705X，因此我的推荐基于我对该型号的体验。</p><p>设置此扩展器非常简单，只需将其插入并按照 TP-Link 的 Tether 移动应用程序中的说明进行操作即可。我尝试过的所有设备都遵循相同的基本设置过程：首先，将扩展器插入路由器附近，按照移动应用程序或设置网页上的说明进行操作，建立连接后，将扩展器移动到您所需的位置。</p><p>将 705X 与我的 Verizon FiOS 路由器配对花了整整五分钟 - 可能最耗时的部分是决定我想为新的 5Ghz 和 2.4Ghz 网络命名。我对两者使用相同的名称，因为我不想在连接手机或笔记本电脑等设备时手动从两个不同的频段中进行选择。该设备会自动将您的设备与适当的频段配对 - 例如，将大多数智能家居小工具连接到 2.4Ghz 网络。</p><p>我移动所有测试的扩展器的永久位置是在我的地下室，因为那是我们可以获得最不稳定信号的地方。我首先使用 Speedtest.net 和 Speedcheck.org 在我的 iPhone 和 MacBook 上运行速度测试，以便我可以将它们与连接到路由器主网络时获得的标准速度进行比较。毫不奇怪，TP-Link 扩展器生成的速度比我的路由器网络的速度慢得多，但我测试的所有设备都是如此。只有我们的高级选择（见下文）接近我的路由器的标准速度，但我预料到了这一点。 WiFi 扩展器不会让您的连接变得<em>更好</em>- 它们只会为您提供更广泛的覆盖范围。从规格角度来看，705X 和 700X 在 5GHz 频段的额定速度高达 2402 Mbps，在 2.4GHz 频段的额定速度高达 574 Mbps。</p><p>尽管我的测试结果如此，但我很高兴地发现我并没有因为 705X 看似较慢的速度而受阻。我像往常一样工作了几个小时，将手机和笔记本电脑连接到扩展器网络，回复电子邮件、在 Slack 中发送消息、流式传输 YouTube 视频以及在 Chrome 中维护几十个选项卡，没有出现任何问题或明显的速度变慢。</p><p>我对 TP-Link 的 Tether 配套应用程序易于使用（虽然有点简单）并不感到惊讶，因为这是我对 TP-Link 智能家居应用程序的体验。 Tether 专门用于该公司的网络设备，在初始设置后您可能不会花费大量时间。我特别喜欢的是，您可以命名连接到扩展器网络的无线设备，例如手机和智能电视。这使得您可以更轻松地了解家中的哪些设备不断与扩展器而不是路由器的默认网络配对。</p><p>使用这些 TP-Link 扩展器需要注意的一件重要事情是，它们都支持<a data-i13n="cpos:3;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:TP-Link;elmt:;" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=79539c2e-109d-49c3-a6ab-ddd018132f09&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=TP-Link&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI3OTUzOWMyZS0xMDlkLTQ5YzMtYTZhYi1kZGQwMTgxMzJmMDkiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudHAtbGluay5jb20vdXMvb25lbWVzaC9wcm9kdWN0LWxpc3QvIiwiY29udGVudFV1aWQiOiJmNTM3YzBjMi1iY2U1LTQyODEtOGQyNy03MDY0ZjVjZmE4YTIifQ&amp;signature=AQAAAWwf_d75L4j9h3fxGIY3iGt9EfZqMMSDc0A_MFnGVKjV&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.tp-link.com%2Fus%2Fonemesh%2Fproduct-list%2F">OneMesh</a> ，这是该公司的一项功能，如果您有兼容的路由器，它允许您创建一个无缝网状网络。 Since I&#39;m still using the router provided to me by my ISP, I wasn&#39;t able to test out this feature, but it works like this: if you have a OneMesh router and OneMesh-compatible extenders, you can link them all together under the same network name. So rather than having a router network and an extender network under the same roof, everything would be linked and filed under your main network&#39;s name.</p><p> It&#39;s a small perk that becomes not so small if you have a spotty extender, or even just an awkwardly laid-out home. In my testing, I found my phone disconnecting from some extenders&#39; networks when I went upstairs to the main floor of the house from my basement. It would then attempt to reconnect to the extender network, when really I would have preferred it to default back to my router&#39;s network. That thankfully didn&#39;t happen with TP-Link&#39;s RE705X, but it&#39;s something to keep in mind when considering buying a WiFi extender at all. If you can get one that has a feature like OneMesh, it&#39;ll make your life much easier.</p><p> Coming in at $130 and $120, respectively, the RE705X and RE700X may not be the cheapest WiFi extenders out there, but their coverage range, WiFi 6 support and max speeds make either of them a good pick. If you know exactly where you want to put an extender and it&#39;s not in an awkward or hard-to-reach location, the slightly cheaper, antenna-free RE700X may work just fine for you. But if you want that extra ability to tweak antennas to suit your needs, the RE705X is the way to go.</p><h2> Best budget: TP-Link AC1200 WiFi extender (RE315)</h2><p><core-commerce id="f66ee2d2ad2d4ff488892c0dc3a46d68" data-type="product-list"></p><p> <a data-i13n="cpos:4;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:;" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAARAk7Y6VLJJUh3LCl0ra0KfYKakt-UEKAQbDtvzsfmF7&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FWifi-Extender-Booster-Wireless-Repeater%2Fdp%2FB08RHD97QY">TP-Link&#39;s RE315 WiFi extender</a> is physically very similar to the RE705X, but with lower specs and that&#39;s what makes it a $50 device. You&#39;ll get up to 867 Mbps speeds on the 5GHz band and 300 Mbps on the 2.4GHz band, and it only provides coverage for up to 1,500 square feet. That won&#39;t be as much of an issue for most people as max speeds will, but if you have a particularly large property, you&#39;re better off going with a more expensive extender that can cover more space.</p><p> There&#39;s also no WiFi 6 support on the RE315, which may be a dealbreaker for those who recently invested in a WiFi 6 router. This model does support OneMesh, though, which is nice if you already have a OneMesh system in your home.</p><p> I&#39;m focusing on specification differences because my experience with the RE315 wasn&#39;t that far off from the RE705X. Setup was just as plain and simple since the RE315 also uses the Tether mobile app, and while speeds were slightly lower in my testing, I didn&#39;t notice too much of a difference in real world use. For $50 normally, and often closer to $30 when on sale, the RE315 is an easy pick for anyone who wants a budget-friendly way to fill WiFi dead zones in their home.</p><h2> Best premium: Netgear AX6000 WiFi 6 mesh range extender (EAX80)</h2><p><core-commerce id="024c0850b69b42948be5d8479b96ad03" data-type="product-list"></p><p> Having more than one WiFi network in your house is par for the course when it comes to adding an extender into the mix. But that&#39;s not so with the <a data-i13n="cpos:5;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:;" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAcTeNyO4rDRAy7Tnip7keUi0BAgrJnfCddrOqMQo6z2f&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FNETGEAR-Nighthawk-Range-Extender-EAX80%2Fdp%2FB07T89YZWD%3Fth%3D1">Netgear EAX80 mesh range extender</a> – it has “seamless smart roaming,” which allows you to set it up under your existing SSID name. So instead of disconnecting from your main network and reconnecting to the extender&#39;s network when you move from your living room to your basement, all you have to do is… move from one room to another and let Netgear&#39;s device do the heavy lifting.</p><p> That&#39;s one of the premium features included on the EAX80, but its $250 price tag can be attributed more so to some other perks. It&#39;s a dual-band, WiFi 6 mesh range extender that will work with pretty much any router you may have. It supports speeds up to 6 Gbps and can have more than 30 devices connected to it at once. As far as square footage goes, it&#39;ll widen your WiFi&#39;s coverage by up to 2,500 square feet, which should be plenty for small and medium-sized homes. It performed well in our speed tests, coming very close to the upload/download speeds I got when being connected to my main network before installing the extender.</p><p> There&#39;s nothing out of the ordinary about the Nighthawk mobile app, which is what you&#39;ll use to initially set up the EAX80 extender. After that, you can use the app to troubleshoot, check WiFi speeds and see which devices are on your network. It&#39;ll likely be a big list since you&#39;ll see everything that&#39;s paired to your router&#39;s network as well. My only gripe is that you can&#39;t edit device names. For example, my den&#39;s TV shows up as “LGwebOSTV” and our soundbar in our basement shows up as “sonyaudio” — but there are a number of connected devices with no name at all, and we&#39;re just stuck with that.</p><p> Aside from its fast speeds and reliable connection, two things set this Netgear extender apart from the other devices I tested. First is that seamless smart roaming feature – not having to switch between WiFi networks when going around my home was super convenient. I never had to worry about my laptop losing connection to a dedicated extender network when I moved from my basement to my second floor, which is something I frequently had to deal with when testing other devices.</p><p> The second differentiating factor is the EAX80&#39;s design. Unlike other range extenders that are chunky blocks that plug directly into an AC outlet, Netgear&#39;s model looks more like a standalone router. While that does mean it has a larger footprint than other devices I tested, it was actually easier to find good spots for it in my home because it didn&#39;t have to be chained to the wall right above an outlet. Most people, especially those tight on space, will probably prefer the standard extender design, but the EAX80 gave me a bit more flexibility. I also appreciated that the EAX80 has four built-in Ethernet ports for physically connecting things like TVs, consoles and more, plus one USB-A port for hardwiring a printer.</p><p> Netgear&#39;s EAX80 range extender is a solid option if you don&#39;t mind dropping a bit of money to get a bunch of convenient features on top of stellar speeds and WiFi 6 support. But it&#39;s worth noting that Netgear has a few options that are similar to the EAX80, but with various differences in speed, coverage and feature set. The most similar is the $130 <a data-i13n="cpos:6;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:;" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAZcnbuwX_Ltn1plqLAQnXCITtcXc8NU-G3byoYW4LwWb&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FNETGEAR-Nighthawk-Range-Extender-EAX80%2Fdp%2FB082X14W5P%3Fth%3D1">EAX20 extender</a> , which includes 1,500 square feet of coverage, support for WiFi 6 and up to 1.8Gbps speeds, plus seamless smart roaming capabilities. The wall-plug version of that, the <a data-i13n="cpos:7;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:;" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAUXQnR7kgAzdZMf-Idjj9_vkqioevyWD-NZH5jQOmItZ&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FNETGEAR-Nighthawk-Range-Extender-EAX80%2Fdp%2FB08K2ZX2RY">EAX15</a> , is actually a tad more expensive at $140.</p> This article originally appeared on Engadget at https://www.engadget.com/best-wifi-extender-130021313.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/best-wifi-extender-130021313.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> f537c0c2-bce5-4281-8d27-7064f5cfa8a2</guid><dc:creator>瓦伦蒂娜·帕拉迪诺</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher>Engadget</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder> Engadget</dc:rightsholder><pubDate> Wed, 26 Jul 2023 14:45:03 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1690382704</ingested><modified> 2023-07-26T14:45:18+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[Technology & Electronics]]></category><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Valentina Palladino]]></category><media:content height="4160" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-03/92857700-c71e-11ed-ae3f-c62e0c68f120" width="6240"><media:keywords> headline </media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_h